'''Otherside Farms''' is a [[medical cannabis]] [[information center]]<ref name=bailey>{{cite news|url=http://articles.dailypilot.com/2010-03-19/news/dpt-potschool032010_1_marijuana-dispensary-medical-marijuana-costa-mesa-city-atty|title=Pot classes in session|first1=Brianna|last1=Bailey|first2=Mona|last2=Shadia|newspaper=Daily Pilot|date=19 March 2010}}</ref> with a separate division<ref name=otherside>{{cite web|url=http://www.Othersidefarms.com|title=Otherside Farms Information Center|publisher=Otherside Farms}}</ref> serving as a private medical cannabis [[collective]].<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.othersidecollective.com|title=Otherside Farms Private Collective|publisher=Otherside Farms}}</ref>
== History == Otherside Farms Cannabis Information Center was opened around 2010 by a [[Newport Beach, California|Newport Beach]] couple, Alysha and Chadd McKeen, hoping their new "medical marijuana information center" would help dissolve stigmas associated with cannabis.<ref name=bailey />
{{Quote|I want to tell people to stop being afraid of it," Chadd McKeen, co-founder of Otherside Farms, told the ''Daily Pilot''. We want to bring it out into the open.<ref name=bailey />}}
The McKeens had a personal incentive to teach people about the benefits of cannabis, as Alysha had gone through [[cancer]] with the help of the plant.<ref name=coker>{{cite news|url=http://www.ocweekly.com/2010-05-20/news/Otherside-farms-chadd-mckeen-medical-marijuana/|title=Growing Pains at Otherside Farms|last=Coker|first=Matt|date=20 May 2010|newspaper=Orange County News}}</ref> City officials approved the location to be legal as long as cannabis was not distributed there.<ref name=bailey />
== Raid == In late August 2011, Otherside Farms opened a private collective, maintaining it as a separate entity from Otherside Farms.<ref name=otherside /> On January 17, 2012, the private collective was raided by federal officials.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://articles.dailypilot.com/2012-01-18/news/tn-dpt-0119-marijuana-20120118_1_marijuana-dispensaries-marijuana-plants-Otherside-farms|title=Authorities raid Costa Mesa marijuana dispensaries|last=Serna|first=Joseph|date=18 January 2012|newspaper=Daily Pilot}}</ref> Controversy ensued over the raid, as city officials had secretly authorized a letter seeking federal law enforcement assistance in shutting down the collective, which an expert claimed was illegal.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://Othersidefarms.com/blog/index.php/News/city-s-secrecy-on-pot-shop-was-illegal-experts-say|title=City's Secrecy on Pot Shop Letter Was Illegal, Expert Says|publisher=Otherside Farms|date=10 February 2012}}</ref> The basis for the raid was an accusation by a city inspector claiming that Chadd McKeen hoped to profit from his business.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://blogs.ocweekly.com/navelgazing/2012/01/dea_raids_several_costa_mesa_m.php|title=DEA Raids Several Costa Mesa Marijuana Dispensaries|last=Schou|first=Nick|date=18 January 2012|newspaper=Orange County News}}</ref> McKeen denied the accusation, stating that his words were misconstrued, and that Otherside Farms had been trying to communicate a plan to help resolve the Cosa Mesa [[budget deficit]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://Othersidefarms.com/blog/index.php/Otherside-FARMS-in-the-NEWS/Otherside-farms-clarification-to-recent-press-coverage|title=Otherside Farms Clarification to Recent Press Coverage|publisher=Otherside Farms|date=18 May 2012}}</ref> that had been present since 2010, only for meeting requests to be turned down by city officials.<ref name=coker />
