'''Social cognition and interaction training''' ('''SCIT''') is a [[cognitive behavioral therapy]] to improve [[social cognition]] with the aim of improving downstream social functioning with people suffering of [[schizophrenia]].<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Roberts |first1=David L. |last2=Combs |first2=Dennis R. |last3=Willoughby |first3=Michael |last4=Mintz |first4=Jim |last5=Gibson |first5=Clare |last6=Rupp |first6=Betty |last7=Penn |first7=David L. |year=2014 |title=A randomized, controlled trial of Social Cognition and Interaction Training (SCIT) for outpatients with schizophrenia spectrum disorders |journal=British Journal of Clinical Psychology |volume=53 |issue=3 |pages=281–98 |pmid=24417608 |doi=10.1111/bjc.12044}}</ref>

In schizophrenia, the ability to adaptively infer the thoughts and feelings of others (i.e., social cognition) is strongly associated with community functioning.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Lahera |first1=G. |last2=Benito |first2=A. |last3=Montes |first3=J.M. |last4=Fernández-Liria |first4=A. |last5=Olbert |first5=C.M. |last6=Penn |first6=D.L. |year=2013 |title=Social cognition and interaction training (SCIT) for outpatients with bipolar disorder |journal=Journal of Affective Disorders |volume=146 |issue=1 |pages=132–6 |pmid=22840617 |doi=10.1016/j.jad.2012.06.032}}</ref>

